TI  - FISH PASSES - AN ECOLOGICAL MEASURE FOR THE RIVER AND HABITAT CONTINUITY PRESERVATION IN THE CRIS RIVER BASIN
PY  - 2011
AB  - River Restoration represents an important domain for water authorities in Europe, especially due to the Water Framework Directive 2000/60/CE which aims at improving the status of rivers ecosystems in a broad, integrated, ecological perspective and to the new Flood Directive. Development of infra-structure projects associated with power supply, abstractions, waste disposal and both rural and urban land-use can all have impacts on the river systems and they threat the bio-diversity and sustainability of flora and fauna including the fish populations. Barriers to fish migration have profound consequences for hydrology and habitats, revering fisheries and upstream and downstream migration of fish. Flood protection is one of the key driving forces causing river and habitat continuity interruption in the Romania country. In Romania there are a small number of fish's passes in four river basins. Most structures, including large barrages, flood-control dams, sluices, flood gates etc., have been built for floods control, water conservation during dry periods, for hydropower, irrigation, for safety or for water supply. This paper focuses on ecological solutions for the fish migration, representing a limited effort related to the achievement of a good ecological status for the heavy modified bodies. Connectivity is crucial in the context of restoration. From a list of 788 reservoirs, only 77 dams/weirs were analyzed, being characterized by surface area above 50 ha and height of the dams until 15 m. The study case has been identified taking into account several criteria such as: the historical fish zone, the present monitoring fish data and the ecological prioritization criteria recommended by the International Commission for the Danube River Protection. The paper presents the ecological solution for the Abramut Crestur reservoir, created in 1976 year, after the sluicing of the Fancica river (total length: 25 km, surface: 100 km(2)) from the Cris River basin. The reservoir is situated in an agriculture area, characterized by low flows and two species of migratory fishes: Barbus barbus and Chondrostoma nasus. Before the embankment the floodplain provided an important habitat and food source (marshland and wet zone covered with reed) for migratory birds and fishes. The proposed ecological solution is to restore natural hydrological functions of the Fancica River by creating a lateral \"natural bypass channel\" for the fish, on the left side of the reservoir, all along the reservoir. Taking into account the neighborhoods of the dams it is enough space for the construction of the fish passes in \"cascade\", being equipped with artificial or natural obstacles such as weirs, stone-blocks and alluvial material mimicking a natural watercourse. The slope of such fish facility will be very slow, and long enough for providing resting areas for the fish. This way the proposedfish way could be an important means of redressing the detrimental effects of obstructions.
